{{dablink|For the 2005 film, see [[Adam & Steve]]}}

'''Adam and Steve''' is a phrase that originated from a [[Judeo-Christian]] argument against [[homosexuality]], in which some [[theologian]]s believe that the natural way of life illustrated by the [[Biblical]] account of creation is the story of "[[Adam and Eve]]," a man and a woman, as opposed to a a man and a man as in "Adam and Steve."

Paul Rudnick's play "The Most Fabulous Story Ever Told" pokes fun at the idea by retelling the creation story with the main characters "Adam and Steve". The story goes on to include good pals (and lesbians) "Jane and Mabel," instead of Cain and Abel, the Biblical sons of Adam and Eve.

A movie and a gay dating service have both been named after this term.

